“The timing for the U.S. rescue operation is uncertain and will affect the global financial markets,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
Hong Kong, although it belongs to China, determines its monetary policy itself, i.e. independent of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. legislators should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and pass the draft financial system support.
Otherwise, more countries would also be affected by the break-in.
A Bloodbath of American Stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected the plan to support the financial system, for which up to $700 billion (nearly 12 trillion K<0xC4><0x8D>) should be spent.
Legislators ignored President George Bush’s call to support the plan.
In Bush’s view, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks suffered a bloodbath on Monday, and major stock indices recorded the largest decline in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index dropped nearly seven percent, with a similar decline last recorded in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there was little evidence that the draft would not pass through in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress Makes Concessions: U.S. Government May Pump $700 Billion Into Banks
The top representatives of the U.S. Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of an agreement on financial assistance to the U.S. financial system.
It will be voted on at the beginning of next week.
U.S. legislators made a breakthrough in talks about passing a bailout plan in the form of $700 billion in financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
However, this does not mean a victory yet.
Congress members have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish the final version of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated in the U.S. Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, chairman of the Banking and Financial Services Committee Barney Frank told Reuters.
The Senate said it was likely to vote on the plan at the earliest on Wednesday.
According to economists, a notification that the plan is being adopted should be the first major psychological factor for a revival of the financial markets.
Afterwards, however, there is a "disenchantment" due to the complicated mechanisms that could help the markets in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our differing views on what a market stabilization package should look like," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to him, a final vote could be held on Sunday.
Legislators met with U.S. Finance Minister Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give the government fund its final form.
This provides for a purchase of unsold mortgage assets from financial companies, which plunge financial firms into heavy losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
“We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
We need to continue the health plan, but I think we’re at the finish line,” Paulson said.
A Signal to Asia Businesses
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are declining sharply.
In the words of the Democratic Senator of Nevada, Harry Reid, legislators are trying to reach a final agreement before Sunday in Congress.
The aim is to reassure investors of doing business on the Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a congressional decision could affect Monday’s business.
Until now, however, it is not entirely clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, and there is also uncertainty as to whether negotiations at the last minute could still fail on a problem.
Legislators hope that it will pass in the next few days.
But the law will still undergo some changes.
The total amount intended to help the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion will be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush called for.
But Congress can block the disbursement of the remaining money if it feels that the program does not perform its function, at another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush considers progress in negotiations positive
