The first virtual provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe...
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all the services offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics at lower prices.
Maybe it won’t wait long.
That the Czech mobile operators work among the most expensive in Europe, we have already reported many times on Mobil.cz.
This was also confirmed by the Telecommunications Authority <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the European Commission’s final steps in the area of roaming fees regulation, there is so likely to be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile carriers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are the prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a fight announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that there is an extremely high level of competition in the Czech market.
The chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>) Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, who in the past had often said that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic, often agrees.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of chances (otherwise, it would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market led to a significant price reduction, to which then also the classic mobile providers had to react.
Before such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, there were similar votes as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been proven that there is room for such providers and that they can really succeed.
By the way, you don’t have to look long for examples.
In February, we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider succeeded in attracting more than 100 thousand customers and thus becoming the country’s fifth-largest provider.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual vendors need far fewer customers than a traditional vendor.
They do not require relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and text messages, which is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to bet on a non-clichéd target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and trust," said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operating company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say if a similar concept as in Poland could also make a foothold in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone press spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epický also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offering."
In the Czech Republic there is no chance, say the mobile operators
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile carrier conquers the Czech Republic, it will not be mobileking.
"While we are talking about an expansion of this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very hopeful.
Mobilking will be more likely to enter the market in other countries in our region,” said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, in a phone call for Mobil.cz.
It indirectly confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything to ensure that there is no potential competitor.
Their interest in launching a virtual mobile provider has long been demonstrated by the GTS Novera Group, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-line, but also mobile telecommunication services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already made progress in negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the Group.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Unofficial information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specificities compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of the Telefónica O2 press department in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other suppliers also point to the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile press spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds, rarely in line with O2’s statement, “So far we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project to continue to build on.”
And she adds: “On the T-Mobile network, hardly any virtual vendor will appear by the end of the year.
At this moment we would have to have a concrete offer already to be able to think in the short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epický says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the best from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
The responsible authorities - with the providers hand in hand
The approach of the mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would be more competition, this would lead to declining prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
So why should we make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull on one strand when it comes to something also proves the long way back and forth about the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> came at the time when U:fon came on the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This is also evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
Now, U:fon is suitable as an argument for why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile carrier.
Given the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services."
Given this approach, however, the total disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which unfortunately does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic, unlike in the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries.
It has the exclusive Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem his very typical attitude.
“The entry into the market of a virtual mobile carrier would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile carrier and a virtual provider about the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential prospects was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic suppliers", according to Kristián Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS in his response to our question.
Of representatives of the suppliers, such a formulation would not come as a surprise.
This is more than worrying for an authority that represents the interests of consumers and, inter alia, ensures that no one abuses its position in the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries, where virtual providers operate normally, it is observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not in the interests of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Really shocking in this case is the almost already stirring harmony of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same gasoline price at the gas stations is certainly only coincidence and the result of a tough competition.
“The Authority has found no evidence in this matter that suggests anti-competitive action, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions in the market.
The necessary instruments for opening up the mobile market for virtual providers are likely to be lacking in the regulatory authority for telecommunications,” Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, drawn up by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the approval of the network operator is always necessary for a virtual provider to enter the market.
And the cellular provider has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily assumes a dominant position in a certain segment.
However, even if you do not follow this argument, it should at least be a warning for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile carriers act strikingly similarly.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when negotiating with all providers.
The transfer of responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a fairly common trick in the telecommunications services, with which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act failed to enforce the extension of the competences of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> to the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS need to know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay when no one looks
First of all, the functioning of any pseudo-virtual providers, of which there are equally many in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but they are only partially public.
Usually these are companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Own mobile phone services, for example, offer Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he will then receive special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual terms with which we will then deal, which can lead to a termination of cooperation with the corresponding company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question on this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not be discussed with the responsible of the mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
The activities of these companies do not give them negligible profits, at the same time they are not affected - unlike the actual virtual providers - by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epický points out possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite this, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it like the normal customers of the mobile carriers.
This alone, however, should at least seem strange to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
Another question opens up for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If the mobile operators close their eyes to such an action, why are they blocking themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has fairly strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the suppliers’ statement that they do not know anything about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been emphasized several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers led to a significant price drop in the various services.
In practically all the countries where virtual providers have been created, the classic providers have tried to prevent their creation practically more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, regulatory bodies intervened at these moments, which in no way sought to safeguard the interests of the mobile operators but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator emerged, and others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing themselves all over the case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that uncertainty in the competences in these cases is more than favorable.
But let's not throw the shotgun in the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon start moving again.
If a provider allows the emergence of a virtual mobile carrier, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will not remain idle when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally not be more expensive to make phone calls than the rest of Europe.
