Prague transport operators also transport on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will go into the history of Prague’s transport companies as a date when the first passengers will board a subway, tram or bus, carrying an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
These can currently be purchased by about one hundred thousand people who have the chip card OpenCard.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it placed on their chip card at the information centers and branch offices of the transport companies at the Muzeum, M<0xC5><0xAF>stek, Nádra<0xC5><0xBE>í, Kaly<0xC5><0xA1>ovice, And<0xC4><0x9B>lis, Letý<0xC5><0x9B>l, Ro<0xC4><0x9B>z
The coupons have been available since yesterday via the Internet on the pages of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use the internet sales can really forget the issue window at the subway stations, where they had to wait regularly in long queues for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon via the Internet, it is played on the open card in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these points there is also a desk with trained staff at the disposal of travelers, which advises prospective buyers on the internet and also places the coupon on the card," said Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the project.
