The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the United States.
The Sudeten Germans had requested the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States in 1945.
This is evident from a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we would like to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten-Germans are said to have turned to the US President in 1945.
This can be seen, among other things, from a letter which has been preserved in a private archive and which is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Krumau in the letter ask the American president not to allow the return of the "Sudetengaus" - which was taken on the basis of the Munich Agreement by Hitler - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units are not entering German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," it said in a letter signed with the words "people to whom the fate of the Sudeten lies at heart."
Since the follow-up to Czechoslovakia suggests that the Sudeten Germans, in the knowledge of the Czech national character, would expect brutality, recklessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take over the protection of the Bohemian Forest for ever and ever.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you have attributed this area to a state foreign to us, which oppresses and tries to eliminate minorities and has contributed nothing at all to the victory of the Allies," the letter read.
The reason why the authors are unable to sign is allegedly the fear of revenge cravings of the “Czech oppressors”.
If the US president has doubts about the sentiment of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it would be sufficient if he initiated a referendum in Bohemian Forest Gauge on whether the inhabitants wanted to become part of the US or live under the protection of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naive in today's knowledge of post-war history, it, however, in the opinion of some contemporary witnesses, draws a good picture of the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at the time.
Although the Bohemian Germans at least had to suspect that they would be negotiated about their deportation from the Republic, only a few of them admitted such an opportunity at all.
Some waited for the United States and Britain to negotiate some sort of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Others believed that they could simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
