Rats also have feelings.
Does a rat or a cockroach flee in danger mean that it also feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
Only how can you check if they feel the same if they behave similarly to us?
For several years, the internet magazine "Edge" has published contributions of famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else having been able to prove this so far, where we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, at least we can hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and address issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter rough terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it stands dead, flees or attacks.
People behave similarly, from which some scientists conclude a comparable subjective experience.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its involvement in short-term memory and execution/control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely missing in other creatures.
At least with those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: since so much of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness does not depend on language, it would certainly affect it, so animal consciousness, whatever it may be, is likely to differ greatly from most of our consciousness states.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor, because of the special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its exploration presents us with great problems.
Most of my remarks relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that should be scientifically more accessible.
One could study the consciousness processes of animals without regard to their contents, and this is exactly what happens in studies of the short-term memory of primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But with this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, one relies more on the neural correlates of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the emergence of visualization.
What does this mean for the sensations?
I trace them back to the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we call “fear” is the mental state we are in when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) proves memory.
In this sense, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that distinguish primates and in particular humans.
Connected with linguistic nature, there are fine gradations of feeling, because we can differentiate and categorize states with the help of words and grammar to attribute them to others besides ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio suggests that sensations from more primitive activities in the body-feeling regions of the cortex and the brain stem arise similar to Jaak Pankseep, which, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could be involved in cross-genus sensations.
Purely theoretically, I cannot disagree with this, but I consider it unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in rats and humans probably feels like this in both cases: But how can one check whether rats and humans feel the same if they behave similarly?
Does a sheep flee in danger if it also feels fear?
In my eyes, mere behavioral similarity cannot yet prove experience equality.
Although the neural comparison continues to help: rats and humans have similar brain strains, cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if it could be proven for humans, how did you want to prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, perhaps even cockroaches (who knows?), have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove that.
And because their sensations are probably fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore the emotional behavior of rats rather than the emotional sensations.
In any case, progress on the neural level is wavering here, as long as you measure the same in rats and humans.
Just as I do not explore language and consciousness in rats, so do not sensations, I do not know if they exist.
You may think that’s shortsighted, but I’d rather move on than constantly running against a wall.
I am a practical emotionalist.
