Debate on bilingual education: Education in an English-speaking environment
In this issue of the Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, Senior Research Fellow in Caliphonic Studies and Senior Director of Educational Sciences at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book “Not As Good As One Thinks: Why the Middle Class Needs a School Selection.”
Addressing Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barrack Obama’s proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign mentions that “the probability of successful completion of school in African-American and Hispanic students is lower than in white students” – which is true.
To close this gap, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends, among others, a bilingual transitional phase in education for those who are first learning English.
Nevertheless, the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school achievements.
Take Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles, for example.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently been in the country, learn English.
Nevertheless, in 2008, astonishing 100 percent of fourth-class students passed the state exam in mathematics at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93% of fourth-year school children were rated as good in the English exam.
This astonishing success has been achieved by methods other than those preferred by Obama.
The Sixth Street School focuses on review and practice, constant control of knowledge, and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
In addition, the school is practicing the approach that education takes place in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly what Obama should be aware of, says school principal Linda Mikels.
This approach attaches importance to the almost exclusive use of the English language in specialized teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school would have a remarkable success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico. 12 months later you would enter the classroom and you would not be able to recognize him.
“It works,” she said, “it works for us.”
Would Obama take a school like the "Sixth Street Prep" as a model for other schools with a large share of Latin American and other English learners?
The school’s achievements would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational positions within his own party (the national picture associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and his own consistent support for bilingual education make predictions about Obama’s answer uncertain.
While agreeing to the point that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about the “English-only” legislation.
Instead, he said, “You should make sure your child can speak Spanish.”
If Obama really wants to close the gap, he must carefully consider educational models that work, rather than contempt and trivialize them.
Oil prices fall due to renewed fears about the economy
Oil prices fell sharply on Monday due to fears that even the U.S. bailout plan for financial markets might not be enough to revive the economy.
Crude oil futures on the New York Stock Exchange fell 7 percent to $99.80 per barrel during the morning session.
Since last Monday, the price has fallen by more than $20.
In the last two weeks, commodity markets have been shaken by both Wall Street financial turmoil and strong hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After peaking at $145.29 per barrel in July, prices dropped to nearly $90 per barrel this month, then rising again as a result of the enormous uncertainty in financial markets.
On Monday, investors again expressed concern, despite congressional representatives announcing that they had agreed on a rescue plan over the weekend, which should be the largest in history.
This news was overshadowed by new concerns that the financial crisis was far from over.
In the foreseeable final chapter of the growing crisis, according to a government statement on Monday, Citigroup is expected to buy the banking operations of Wachovia Corporation.
In the meantime, Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partially nationalized the European financial group Fortis.
According to analysts at Barclays Capital, despite the tense negotiations that took place over the weekend and led to a bailout plan, it appears to have failed to revive the mood in the markets.
As the economic situation continues to deteriorate, demand for goods, including oil, is expected to continue to decline.
Analysts from Deutsche Bank have written in a statement to investors that forecasts for global capital markets, interest rates and exchange rates have become extremely uncertain.
We believe they will continue to write that the goods markets will also be affected.
“From the perspective of the goods markets, we are most concerned about whether the US virus is spreading worldwide, especially to China.”
Analysts have corrected their expectations for oil consumption due to weak economic growth for the coming year, and lowered their forecasts for oil and gas prices for 2009 by 20%.
