The pride and hardships in the lives of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden among the thrills of theme parks around Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, loud and gigantic hustle and bustle, is a quiet city where the pride and complications of African American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first completely black city in the country and hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquettes, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Nowadays it is a pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous Harlem Renaissance author.
And yet, the city that describes it – and which made it a tourist destination by taking it to the Florida Travel Guide produced by the Federal Writers’ Project in times of depression – is and remains in many ways a very special place.
Eatonville is as independent, wealthy and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he does not know what he misses."
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidacy, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open conversation about racial relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
“We’re very keen on how our story is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, from birth to a town resident and community member of the city’s oldest church.
It must be right."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of nearly 2,400 inhabitants in which the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other hand, an example of the - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
It’s no surprise that the locals are both proud and on guard.
And the concerns about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in language, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973).
Five paragraphs in the Florida Guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Freaky as Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the shop of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Away from the road to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-white painted modern school, with its well-kept gardens and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always cares about, although he can barely read and write."
She also mentioned the new husband of widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of any kind and whatever fits into hour rooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by everyone.
“Zora described things as they were,” said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston by quoting the men singing songs about her beauty that were full of sexual allusions.
She added, “Some people didn’t like it.”
One still remembers Hurtson as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembered that when Hurston came to the city brewed, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy chevrolet, smoking and dressed in pants, in a city that even today imagines something about her venerable style of clothing.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the inhabitants were fascinated, while many despised them.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” said Mr. Franklin.
But "she never stayed too long," he added as he rocked in his chair, on a back-facing terrace overlooking the Sabelia lake, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Together with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous tomb in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville there was no major commemoration, no public readings on a grand scale.
“I don’t think they understood their contribution to the world or their legacy at all,” said Valerie Boyd, author of Wrapped in Rainbows, a biography about Hurston published in 2003.
The turnaround came in the 1980s.
Orange County authorities wanted to put a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community’s slow two-lane main road.
Orlando’s suburbs had already pushed the Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult phase in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred to the community.
“At that time, a bunch of white boys often came and threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting away,” said Mr. Franklin.
“There was even a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car.”
In 1955, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand to enforce integration by calling its decision in Brown's case against the school council "insulting rather than respecting my race."
Residents nowadays say that although the lifting of racial segregation was positive in some ways, it weakened the group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
“Black children were used to being hugged — I remember — they hugged their teacher in the morning and hugged their teacher in the evening,” said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the non-profit Eatonville Community Protection Group.
This could be maintained until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You didn't hug his white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural divide," Ms. Nathiri said.
However, civil rights have helped to make room for more Zora Neale Hurstons – black writers, actors, and artists who overcame prejudices, just as she did, with positive self-confidence and statements like, “How can anyone deny the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker set out for Hurston's nameless tomb and began to fight for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much-promised Hurston biography of Robert E. Hemenway was found on the bookshelves, and made it again a part of the American literary canon.
The highway project came at a time when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The municipality began planning a Hurston festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans of a five-lane highway revived the city, accelerated the whole with top speed, aroused genuine citizen pride," said Ms. Nathiri.
Mrs. Boyd put it a little easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project has contributed to a change in the city’s self-image.
More and more people came along, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to reappraise the past.
Eatonville was added to the national historical register in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville is still a peculiarity in Florida: just 6 miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It is 90% black nowadays.)
Outsiders in search of the history of Eatonville and its meaning are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, prior permission is required and certain things - such as the wall painting of Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men at fieldwork - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a brave, confident teacher with a fondness for dark red, still fear that their shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival grew larger, an increased degree of home pride was born.
Above all, young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw their entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better, and just as proud, creative and diligent, silly and mixed as any other race and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or the police, which he says might need some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
“Most people who only pass through here will think, ‘Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,’” Alondra Kenon said on a Sunday after church.
“But if you actually stop and look at your history for a moment, it’s a very beautiful city.”
Here in New York, we speak fluent financial Latin.
At first glance nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan were to stay away from the newspaper stands and the huge television screens in Times Square, they wouldn’t realize they were in the middle of a debacle.
They would never believe that above their heads, in the shoebox-like offices with the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ades, bankers and hedge fund managers who have the monopoly in New York City, have the worst day of horror every day since the stock market crash of 1929.
The suppliers still push the metal tea carts along sidewalks with loud rattles and carry trays loaded with muffins for breakfast sessions.
Latinos still swirl around between apartments, as human packed animals loaded with around 50 ironed T-shirts hanging on a yoke-like rod lying on their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting for their breakfast bag on the sidewalk food stalls and it is still impossible to get a yellow taxi on a weekday between 4 and 7 pm.
It didn’t feel like a crisis at all until Thursday afternoon due to all the world’s ending rumours, I decided to open a new savings account.
Although I had decided to put my compulsory course on the quiet late afternoon at my JP Morgan Chase branch, there were already about 20 people standing in line.
Not at the cash desk to withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service desk where regular customers order checkbooks, tourists ask about the way to Macy's department store and where new customers open accounts.
Most of them before me, as I later learned from Starr, my "personal banker with license," were queues for the same reason as me.
However, unlike me, they had already taken their savings from smaller banks, to places from which they commuted, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Staten Island.
They had withdrawn money from so-called thrifts (a bit like a construction savings bank), cooperative banks and those local savings banks that only have branches in one state, saying they treat their customers like family.
Last year, 15 of these banks went silent and quietly bankrupt.
In the last few days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went into bankruptcy management and when last Friday New Yorkers drove home over the weekend, Wachovia, another bank that owns savings assets worth $440 billion, was looking for a rescue buyer.
In fear of another collapse, the office and shop workers who stood in front of me brought their bars to a bank that is considered a safe haven, a bank that is responsible for most rescue purchases on Wall Street.
Very normal New Yorkers have acquired flowing financial Latin in recent weeks.
A woman who was on the phone in my main Chinese supermarket referred with so much acquaintance to Lehman Brothers, the bankruptcy bank, and their fattened-looking CEO Dick Fuld, as if she were blaspheming about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the 50-year-old uniformed concierge of my apartment block, has departed from our usual entertainment topics about Brad and Angelina and my grocery delivery.
"I now have all my savings in money market funds," she told me after my visit to the bank.
"I've changed, I'm not going to take any more risks."
