Drivers who may fall back due to the alcohol level will need to install the <0x60>Alcolock'.
The authority orders that the driver, who had three official penalties for alcohol levels, install in his car this system, which prohibits him from starting the car in a drunk state. If he is alcoholic, then the car does not jump.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the report of the Attorney General's Office, which says it is a pilot project that will last for a year.
The purpose is to rehabilitate the driver, which is why he gets a course for retraining traffic behavior.
In addition to the Attorney General’s Office, the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for Safety of Automobiles will also participate.
According to statistics, between 30-75 percent of drivers who were shown under the influence of alcohol more than once regained control.
The ‘alcolock’ would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air and prevents car start when the driver has done an alcohol test; or when an alcohol concentration is detected that is higher than allowed.
It costs more than 1,000 euros, the costs are borne by the one who imposes the sanction.
In this context, a study conducted in the U.S. in 2007 showed that cars equipped with these devices prevent up to 65% of rule violations in the first year after their introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved annually.
The measure is limited to administrative penalties for two reasons: to tackle this behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And to facilitate their implementation, a lawful reform can be implemented in the ordinary way, and yet a reform of the Basic Law is called for, which is necessary for the prosecution process.
The device is still not available in the Spanish markets, in any store, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
The House of Representatives will vote tomorrow on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses, and this has already been done in France.
