Conversation - From the blood that was safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to be pleased as Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
Above all, it has regained the trust of the public, which had been severely shaken by the blood contamination scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As it is known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross blood donation service were contaminated with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the light of this drama and public dissatisfaction, the Government of Canada initiated a public inquiry, led by Judge Horace Krever, in February 1994, aimed at shedding light on the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and drawing up guidelines to prevent a further disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to issue his report, several provinces at the time set up a committee whose goal was to develop a new system for managing blood cans in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
“In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started working, hardly 38% of people had confidence in the blood canning system in Quebec,” recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
“Through the tremendous efforts to improve the safety of blood cans and by working in this field over the following years, we have regained the public confidence,” she says, before proudly stressing that nearly 94% of Quebec’s population had confidence in Hema-Quebec in early 2008.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its inception on September 28, 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted on the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the appearance of numerous cases of the human form of cattle insanity in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman, who has been in charge since the foundation of 1998.
“And we didn’t have the slightest idea whether this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we referred to one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which exclusion measures are applied when you do not know this and when a disease progresses slowly, as is evidently the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, manifested by degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
Thus, in April 1999, no blood was taken from persons who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, it was proven without any doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied is quite meaningful.
In 1999, a much more precise technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NSTs), which allow the detection of the presence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NSTs made it possible to shorten the incubation time that occurs between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and could not be detected, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, that means that you would have to distribute 12 million cans of blood before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood preserves each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case occurs in which HIV was transmitted through a blood preserve.
I think you can feel comfortable nowadays when you get a blood transfusion or prescribe it to restore health," says the chief executive of Hema-Quebec.
“Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogens can get into the system.
It was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the Westnil virus, is transmitted through the blood by insects.
We need to monitor continuously,” Dr. Décary continues, before emphasizing that Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate supplies in addition to a safe supply.
“Demand is rising as the population ages.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population also affects the blood donor network, which on average only comprises 3% of Quebec’s population eligible for blood donation.
Any healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is widespread are excluded from blood donation for a year.
“With these 3%, we manage to get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But you need to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It’s hard to convince people to donate blood, but especially to keep them and make them become regular donors.
“Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour giving blood,” said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only preserved blood, but also human tissue, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is used almost exclusively for severe fire injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec’s only public umbilical cord blood bank.
In the umbilical cord, which was previously considered biomedical waste, there is blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to lose more than a thousand a year.
“We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year,” Dr. Décary continues, describing this program of umbilical cord blood loss as very popular.
‘Many mothers are convinced they don’t have access to it,’ because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
