Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Deputy Director General of the Canadian Barrick Gold Mine.
This confirms, and pursues an Orwellian logic, that the world’s largest gold mining company sought a defamation lawsuit of over six million against three authors and a small resourceless publishing house, with the aim of opening a ‘transparent public debate’.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge the truth, especially not in the case of defamation lawsuits, but the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to represent one of their opposite opinions.
No matter what the trial ends, the authors and publishers of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid from the nearly inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactic in these unequal struggles is, moreover, often to ruin the defenders in order to enforce a consensual settlement that silences the other side and also deters anyone who dares to deal with the question again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things to public opinion.
In contrast, what is commonplace in many of the countries where Barrick works gold, debates in Canada are usually held by exchanging ideas rather than by sticking.
It would have been enough, therefore, if the gold mine had disclosed its books and files and opened a real debate through the newspapers, media, publications and the financing of independent audit teams that could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and wipes away the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada with a hand movement.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he can ask for a 'public' debate at the same time and yet disregard the opinions of this public?
Apparently this word in the world of the Vice-President encompasses only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a rather narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanders have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand – or does not want to understand – is that the public supporting the authors and editors of Noir Canada does so primarily because they reject the brutal stance of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not within a framework that many perceive as a gag complaint (in the course of the ‘public debate’, Barrick Gold has just made a demand to the authors of Noir Canada that they no longer use that term...).
Aside from Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and truth-finding that is fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to quote credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to explore and discuss issues that do not please the rich companies of this world, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long known how to deal with debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate, and it is time for governments to take action to limit this kind of unjustified lawsuit.
