The psychology of overbidding - or why we're willing to pay more
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the filed.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to beat themselves in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have attempted to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was to play the lottery, while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, participants were able to win money, but increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cortex, was measured in losers of the auction, in which the opponent's overbidding plays a major role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to underpin their thesis, the economists in the research group have additionally carried out research to track the money.
In this case, three groups should compete against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward in case they emerged as winners from the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was only that the emphasis on one was on winning, while on the other was on losing.
As evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the "against losing" group were willing to take higher stakes than those in the control or the "win" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have justified the behaviors observed at auctions so far only with the joy of winning, or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see the doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected is estimated at one hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
Symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in the case of hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food or water), in the case of hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vaginal secretion or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to be vaccinated against the viruses A and B, in any case, there is no vaccine against the virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after consuming the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, the jaundice appears on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes bright, the urine becomes dark, and recovery can last up to two-three weeks.
Around 1 million people worldwide die each year from the far more serious diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people are on drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups where this disease is more common: those who underwent blood transfusions before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed.
Currently, the number of people suffering from chronic hepatitis C is estimated to be 200 million worldwide.
Since the disease is already detectable during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult the GP at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognized in time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby banning the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, the first World Hepatitis Day to be hosted by patient representatives worldwide in 2004.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of this chronic liver infection caused by viruses, its emergence and the importance of early detection.
