Recent research shows that religious faith acts as a kind of “pain remedy” that has already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment: it investigated the extent to which belief in God influences human pain, the British newspaper "Telegraph" reported.
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electroshocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the believers were able to eliminate most of the pain.
A brain scan technology even proved that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
The study was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from different departments of the university participated.
During the experiment, the subjects were attached to the left hand with a sparkling device, which gave off the electric shocks.
Participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: on the one hand a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke some kind of religious trance among the believers, while selecting da Vinci’s picture because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt as reassuring.
The subjects each spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time received a total of 20 electroshocks in four stages, while looking at either the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they felt "safe" at the sight of the Mother of God as if they were "concerned" and felt "rest and peace".
While looking at the religious painting, they reported about 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, said that you could create similar effects with other, strongly acting images, even among atheists, you just need to find the corresponding photo.
“We need to find an image that triggers very positive sensations, such as a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
“Practicing the faith should change our personality, and so does it in many cases,” Wright said.
After these excellent results, the only question remains what effect a Madonna image of Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the pain regulation of the believers.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On the occasion of its tenth birthday, Google is right to say that it can be found in people’s pockets as well as above their heads in the sky: it knows where people spent their holidays, which specialists they go to, and what moves them.
And that’s still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the CEOs of Google.
In the direction of skeptics plagued by Orwell’s horror visions, he points out that they would just overlook the essence of Web 2.0.
In an interview with the Financial Times, Schmidt recently said Google’s main goal was to collect even more personal data about users and thus get closer to the company’s original goal of “arranging all the information in the world.”
Schmidt said that after ten years of world-changing work, Google is still only at the beginning of information gathering.
Asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said: he wished Google would be able to answer questions like "What should I do tomorrow?" or "Which job really suits me?", but software programs were not yet able to do so because they did not know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that in the course of their Internet searches the search terms would be recorded, as well as the IP addresses from which they were searched, and the pages visited.
For example, the "Personalized Search" introduced two years ago allows the visitor to save their own search history and later rely on it so that the hits can be generated much more accurately later, and on the same logic are also the so-called "recommendations", with which the system recommends customized products and services based on previous preferences.
However, users wonder what happens in case of data abuse - "When you look at what I'm doing" - some are worried about the Google data monopoly.
In most cases, however, it is more the potential power represented by the company that is fearful, and less the guilt or fear of punishment, the pursuit of freedom, or the rebellion against the power that many internet users encounter.
However, it is a proven fact that the search terms are not only stored, but are also passed on to third parties in the event of such a transaction, and in these cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the Internet user.
A prime example of this was recently the action against pedophilia in Brazil, in the course of which Google handed over information to the Brazilian government collected by the community site called "Orkut" and also enabled the identification of pedophilias.
However, users concerned about personal rights were able to breathe in May, when Google successfully tried the FBI together with the civil rights organization EFF: accordingly, Google can not be forced in the future with any point of the constitution to release information to the FBI on a secret request.
(However, the Federal Government has successfully obtained the release of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms with reference to the Youth Protection Act passed years ago, however, it was deprived of the list of individual users, respectively their web and search terms list for two months retroactively.)
So Google’s image remains controversial: Those who reluctantly release their personal data because they fear the loss of their privacy and privacy through the use of Google services, are scourging the company with the outrage due to the conservative companies.
Meanwhile, the American “geek culture” that is present in many countries and unites enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users sees the next generation of “cool entrepreneurs” in them, unlike Microsoft, which is the market leader thanks to Windows, even though both are fighting for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that unlike Microsoft, Google does not require its users identification codes, and provides its services for free, making an open, constantly updated source code and program package seem far more attractive, youthful and cool than the software giant’s official practices.
On the other hand, the geeks see through the problematic relationship of personal rights and the Internet sharp - a relationship that has come to the fore in particular in recent years thanks to the term "Web 2.0".
The "Web 2.0" is about nothing more than collaboration, that is, the users deliberately leave traces and use the available communication channels, and even if the dimensions are individually different, the main thing remains the same, namely to show themselves publicly.
An average teenager can simultaneously manage his profile on multiple community portals - from Facebook to Xanga, he can connect them through other services, such as Twitter, or music services such as last.fm, and can eventually embed all of this into a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. In addition, they can run blogs that represent the latest photo galleries automatically on Flicktets or Picasa.
And a number of other exemplary cases proves: When looking at the party photos of last night, the girlfriend soon finds out who her unfaithful friend has enjoyed, or the employee is fired because he is only too honest about his anger about the management of the company - one thing is certain: the term "privacy" has now been completely reinterpreted.
The person who leads an online life is what he reveals of himself - that is how one could in fact formulate the basic idea behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who tries to keep something secret, or even bypass the Google monopoly, can do so - such as with Scroogle, a tool that accesses Google's search engine, but deliberately leaves no traces.
Many people do not deliberately register on community sites, so that they are not findable, but also the online applications of Google, such as text processing and graphic tools and RSS feeds, can be handled with alternative versions that are not bound to huge server parks and therefore do not generate the best possible profile of the user.
However, public opinion is waiting for Google to show its true face.
With its current value of $156 billion, the company is even ahead of IBM (USD 140 billion), Intel (USD 124 billion) or Coca-Cola (USD 110 billion), AdWords/AdSense’s advertising space threatens advertising agencies’ revenues, and the rapidly-introduced services are causing headaches not only for Microsoft, but also for other software developers.
Critical viewers, however, also find the disturbing opposing poles: for example, the Group management completely rejected a protest by employees, after the fees of the company’s own kindergarten were doubled, in addition, the management said that the repeated feeding of employees was too costly. But all this mutes quite mildly against the idea that in 2006 Google went to the Chinese government, even in the face of a protest.
The internal regulation of the group is that no new service is advertised in advance, but only when it is already available. Nevertheless, the events of the coming months and years could again turn a lot strongly: While some believe that Google's book and magazine scanning or archiving project is now completely assumed that the company would soon have to deal with the Supreme Court, the other are rather the problem of the system.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database already provides the next generation of sci-fi authors with the stuff - for example, "Scroogled", the famous novel by Cory Doctorow describes in the best Orwellian way a future in which a person becomes terrifyingly close thanks to data collected by Google.
