Intelligent car imitates the flight of the hummingbirds
What would be the best way to develop new technologies to prevent accidents if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented, in which Nissan engineers were inspired by bumblebees to create new accident-preventing systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C-type biomimetic system, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, to support the development of a system that avoids collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protection shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
In order to mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is registered in fractions of a second, and the autorobot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees, by rotating the tires around the appropriate angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
"If it weren't, the autorobot couldn't respond quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Autorobot Project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they dodge other bees.
And this must happen in a fraction of a second.
However, the dodging, unlike the bees, can not be done up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the turnability of the matures.
While there are infinite possibilities for the bees to avoid other bees, the researchers were only able to use the rotational movement, or the acceleration and deceleration, in the case of the autorobot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer service life than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and respond to them accordingly.
It does not have to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical response based on previous maneuvers, so that it constantly takes only a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of instant collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could be the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately guiding the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to his destination.
