Industrial prices continue to rise
According to the Central Statistical Office, domestic sales prices rose 0.1 percent compared to the previous month in August 2008 and 12.9 percent compared to August 2007.
Export prices were 1.1 per cent higher than in July 2008 and fell 3.9 per cent from the previous year's prices.
Due to domestic and export price changes, production prices were 0.7% higher than in the previous month and 3.2% higher than in 2007.
Domestic sales prices have only slightly increased compared to the previous month, i.e. by 0.1 percent.
The sales prices of the manufacturing industry have also risen only slightly - 0.1 percent - since July.
The biggest price increase in August 2008 was for leather goods (2.8 percent) - mainly for bags and belts - here the increase was 4.6 percent, for shoes prices rose by 2.5 percent.
Higher prices for plastics and chemical raw materials pushed prices for chemicals and production up significantly (1.6 percent).
Price decreases were recorded in crude oil processing (1.4 per cent), electrical and technical equipment (0.9 per cent), and wood processing (0.1 per cent).
Prices in papermaking, publishing and printing remained unchanged.
In other branches of the manufacturing industry, a price increase of between 0.2 and 0.9 percent was measured.
In the major domestic sales markets of industry, such as electricity, gas, steam and water supply, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, primarily as a result of the gas price increase introduced on July 1.
Considering the domestic sales markets of the manufacturing industry year-on-year, prices in crude oil processing have risen the most (32.4%).
In the metal-processing sector, a 13.2% increase was observed, while the increase in food, beverage, and tobacco production was 11%.
A decrease in prices was observed in the textile industry (2.5 percent) and in electrical and technical equipment (0.3 percent).
In the other manufacturing industries, the level of inflation was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry rose by 10.2 percent last year.
Prices for electricity, gas, steam and water rose by 18.7 percent compared to the previous year.
In the domestic sales market, the highest price increase in the asset sector was recorded in August (0.7 percent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices rose 0.3 percent, while they remained the same in the energy and processing sectors compared to the previous month.
The largest price increase in August 2008 was observed in the energy and reuse sector compared to the 2007 comparison period (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods manufacturing sectors, a price increase of 6.8 percent was recorded, while in the asset sectors, a price reduction of 1.4 percent was recorded.
Industry export prices measured in Forint rose in August by 1.1 percent compared to the previous month, but declined by 3.9 percent year-on-year.
The domestic currency weakened by 1.7% compared to the euro, the dollar by 7.1 percent, and compared to the August 2007 rate, it was 7.5% stronger compared to the euro, even 15.9% stronger than the dollar.
