Járóka: The vicious cycle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today the European Summit on Equal Opportunities began in Paris, which will be hosted this year by the country of the Presidency of the Council of the European Union France.
In her speech to the plenary, Livia Járóka, Fidesz MEP of the European People’s Party, drew attention, in particular, to the segregation of education, as it is one of the most serious violations of rights against Roma children, and it is also the biggest obstacle to their need for applicability.
The high-level conference was opened by the French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, Xavier Bertrand, on behalf of the French Presidency, and Vladimir Spidla, Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among the participants were representatives of governments, the European social partners, as well as the most important European legal protection and civil society organisations in the field of equal opportunities.
According to the press office of Fidesz MEPs, Járóka has warned that, in addition to discrimination in job-seeking, Roma would be displaced from the labour market primarily because of their low level of education.
"The vast majority of Roma youth do not have a middle school education, and thanks to poor primary education, only a small proportion of them can achieve a university degree."
Furthermore, Járóka stressed that education is a fundamental human right that would play a key role in the assertion of other human rights.
Investing in early education for Roma children could strengthen the economy of the EU Member States.
In the opinion of the MEPs, it is important that a broader circle - Roma and non-Roma - become aware of these connections.
The sooner a Roma pupil starts school, the greater his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market; and through income and sales tax they contribute to national spending.
"As citizens of the Union, Roma must be guaranteed the right to high-quality education - poor and segregated education must be discontinued" - says Lívia Járóka.
As the MEP explained, a common, objective and action-oriented approach by the European Union is necessary to speed up the process of disintegration in the education sector, in order to ensure that the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives are correctly complied with.
“We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation, and unemployment and give Roma children democratic opportunities to contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens,” Járóka said.
Since the Congress in Berlin last year, the summit has been held annually with the aim of creating a unique forum for the advancement of the objectives of equal opportunities and freedom from discrimination at European as well as national level, in the sense of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities".
