Napolitano: "Prevention of accidents at work is crucial"
Every day, 2500 accidents occur in Italy, three people die and 27 remain disabled for life.
For 2007, data from the Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul lavoro confirm that the fatalities at work were around 1200.
These numbers prove the seriousness of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as are caused by murder.
Today, in all the provinces of Italy, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) will celebrate the 58th National Day for the Victims of Work Accidents, in order to draw the attention of social institutions and the media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data disseminated by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm the decisiveness of the issue of workplace prevention," said the President of the Republic, Giorgio Napolitano, in his communication to the President of the Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The head of state expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to preventing jobs, protecting injured workers, helping victims' families and raising public awareness".
"There has been an outrageous 'basta' on this; understandably in the case of tragedies that, in terms of their magnitude, provoke some vortices in the media and public sympathy, but everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events that can even repeat themselves in their own dynamics."
Napolitano does not hide that "there is definitely also a resource problem: there must be decisive investment in education and information."
The numerous initiatives for a more direct awareness in school settings by young people who feed on the world of work are of particular importance.
It is our duty to pay attention to this phenomenon and not to distract from its social seriousness; we must put in place and improve a legislative norm.
For his part, the President of the Chamber Gianfranco Fini stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency that offends the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards decisive rules that aim to put an end to the problem".
"The data on occupational accidents seem to signal a slight improvement, but this does not preclude that the number of work-related deaths is far too high," said Anmil President Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this 'positive tendency' to mean less attention. That's exactly what causes the tragedy in the end."
"How do you believe that basically not enough is done to counteract the phenomenon of accidents? You can fight against it through various actions.
In our opinion, stronger controls and inspections are necessary – according to Mercandelli; but also stronger measures to educate workers who are already starting at school.”
"A further effort is needed - he adds - in terms of communication and raising awareness of public opinion.
But above all, there is a need for a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers vis-<0xC3><0xA0>-vis a phenomenon that represents a social emergency."
Mercandelli also spoke of the "progressive deterioration of protection for victims of accidents at work" and denounced the "abolition of the social system against which we are fighting in recent years".
"The aim is, therefore, to give back to the worker a guarantee of insurance so that the fate of the victim of a work accident does not depend on voluntary or random donations decided from time to time by a legislature."
