Students are victims of high rental prices of up to 900 euros per room
The student housing market has no crises.
According to the latest investigation by Sunia, the tenant union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken on very serious traits, so many students lose their right to study because their families are unable to support them at this level," says the officials of the Sunia, Laura Mariani, "in these cities, the high demand on the part of the students leads to a deformation of the market, which has also damaged the other inhabitants.
In addition, most rental offers include a number of violations: free contracts, missing registrations, no rental price limit, unauthorized sublets.
For the Sunia, there is a need for exceptional measures, which lead to lower rental prices through a revision of the taxation.
A closer look at the investigation shows that in Milan a sleeping space in the Brianza district is needed about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Bande Nere district) and ends with 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera district or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence, a sleeping space costs an average of 350/400 euros, a room costs 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in the neighborhoods around the university, 250/280 euros are for a sleeping place of need, 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, the prices in the neighborhoods around the university are around 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a sleeping space in a double room.
Only slightly lower are the rents in the neighbourhoods around the other universities of Rome: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>.
Only those who dodge in outer districts can save money: 300 euros for a sleeping place and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar quarters.
In Naples you need 300-450 euros for a bed, for a room the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive neighborhoods, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, a sleeping area costs 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350 euros.
In the smallest cities, prices are lower, but they have a greater weight in the urban economy.
In cities where the phenomenon of renting to non-European students is more common, such as in Perugia, there is even another anomaly: a rent that is 25-30% above the average is demanded by foreign students.
Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinemas
The historic cinemas close due to the favored multiplex cinemas.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
This picture by the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening at the moment in the great urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, in the long run means death for the one-room cinema in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also bears the characteristics of a cultural crime.
It is like losing a friend with whom you have walked a street full of emotions, according to the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who earned him the Oscar and the Cannes Grand Prix 20 years ago. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a world well lost forever.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the tremendous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; most of them paid for the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This testifies to the fact that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the lists, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "although it is useful that new structures also emerge, the first priority is to preserve the already existing, because closes a hall in the city, not all its regular customers are ready to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old.
And here still remains the lack of budget for the fund of the trade association: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a shame from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
To maintain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros a year would be needed."
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, due to the fears of the old cinemas, decided to protect them through an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first agreement of its kind in Italy aimed at protecting and supporting traditional cinemas, both in the historical center and in the periphery.
Among the measures envisaged are also tax benefits for cinema operators and benefits for the public with regard to local transport: it will be allowed to drive to the traffic-limited areas of the center and also to park at lower parking fees.
“It is a delightful initiative,” says Giuseppe Tornatore, “I hope that other cities will follow our example and also develop new concepts.
Certainly, we also need better audio and video equipment to be able to align against the superpower of multiplex rooms, because, after all, the audience today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the idea for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years; when I pass by the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside not to have to see the dusty posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to adapt the decisions of the community to the interests of the Piromalli mafia group.
The accusations of the anti-mafia authority of Calabria against Mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the municipality of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning for involvement in mafia business, are serious.
Gioacchino Piromalli, the elder intermediary between the clan and the public administration, and his nephew were also handcuffed: the lawyer, who bears the same name as the head of the clan, had already been convicted of involvement in criminal associations of the mafia, at the time to a sum of 10 million euros in compensation.
"In disregard of any moral and legal norm," the lawyers wrote, "the two local administrations had decided to pay lawyer Piromalli funds for advisory activities."
“This made it possible for the mafia group – according to the judges – to officially invade the town halls and determine the policy of public administration.”
The President of the Calabrian Regional Committee Agazio Loiero does not deny that in his region "it is anything but an exception to encountering links of local administrations and organized crime." "There are places where the concentration of the mafia is greater than in others, where such links are practically inevitable.
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'Ndrangheta: heroes who preserve a white vest."
This morning’s arrests follow those of last July, with which, according to the police, the Piromalli clan was beheaded.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, but already in 1991 – and also at the time due to alleged links between organized crime and local administration – local politicians had been removed from their municipal offices.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the Udc, was elected head of the centre-right coalition after the May 2006 election.
He shouted scandal when the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipality council.
He accused Vice Minister of the Interior Marco Minniti of having invented everything for political and strategic reasons, but the judges say in connection with this morning’s arrest warrant that the Piromalli clan had even dared to request a change to the A3 project.
A hearing action in connection with the investigations into the Dal Torrione case has shown the willingness to meet the wishes of an entrepreneur, who is known to be a representative of the large group around the Piromalli – thus making the actions of the public administration identical with the interests of this clan.
When the energy comes out of the waves, the big ones suddenly run up.
It is a non-drying source of money that covers over 70% of the planet’s surface and only now do the big energy companies of the world seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is looking at and looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years; not accidentally, these studies intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980, the idea of marine energy was forgotten, but now the environmental organisations and the rising oil price are pushing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world’s energy needs could be met by the energy generated by ocean waves.
This would be equivalent to twice the current energy produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there are also the currents and tides.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are now relying on marine energy production.
“Chevron is investigating these technologies,” said the spokesman of a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal, “and is considering the possibility of working with us.”
This is about acquiring an approval from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially considering that oil is still being pumped by the United States in Alaska and that President Bush has only recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, observers speak of an increasing interest.
And technologies that can be improved.
Experts speak of a technology still in the making, not least because the last doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of rather small dimensions and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, to produce energy on a large scale, it requires technologies with far greater impact on the environment.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is sent to the coast via underwater pipes.
So far, there are four planned installations of this type, which are only awaiting state approval. Part of the energy obtained could also be used for military facilities.
Verdant Power, however, is already producing power for a department store and a parking lot using undersea turbines in New York’s East River.
The water movements during the tide drive the turbines, which feeds the generator due to the rotary movement that arises.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Recovery Research, the potential in the tides deserves a particular interest right now.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, sunlight and also waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is the tide energy that led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to already invest $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
